{{short description|c. 1736–1738 painting by William Hogarth}}
{{italic title}}
[[Image:William Hogarth 017.jpg|thumb|275px|right|''Scene from Shakespeare's The Tempest'' by Hogarth; Circa 1735]]

'''''Scene from Shakespeare's The Tempest''''', also known as '''''Ferdinand courting Miranda''''' ({{circa|1736–1738}}) is an oil painting by the English painter [[William Hogarth]].{{sfn|Paulson|1992|p=200}} It has been displayed at [[Nostell Priory]] since 1766, and was acquired by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in 2002.  The National Trust claims that it is "the first known painting of a scene from Shakespeare".{{sfn|National Trust Collections|n.d.}}{{sfn|Pask|2013|pp=54–55}}

The painting is a rich and vibrant example of Hogarth's work, painted c.1730-5 as a special project for one of his devoted band of patrons—[[George Parker, 2nd Earl of Macclesfield|The Earl of Macclesfield]]—as part of Hogarth's attempt to found an distinctively British school of history painting. It is thought that Hogarth was hoping that more commissions for similar scenes would come flowing in after painting this scene, but this did not happen.{{sfn|Art Fund|2002}}{{sfn|Tate Britain|n.d.}}

It measures {{convert|80|x|106.5|cm}} and depicts a scene from Act 1 scene ii of [[William Shakespeare]]'s play, ''[[The Tempest]]'', with [[Ferdinand (The Tempest)|Ferdinand]] courting [[Miranda (The Tempest)|Miranda]]. Miranda is depicted sitting on a throne made of shells and coral, distracted and thus spilling from a bowl of milk that she has been feeding to a lamb.  To the left is her father [[Prospero]], and further left is Ferdinand.  The spirit [[Ariel (Shakespeare)|Ariel]] floats above, playing a [[lute]] or [[mandolin]].  To the right is the misshapen monster [[Caliban (character)|Caliban]], with a bat above his head, grimacing and drooling as he stamps on a dove.{{sfn|National Trust Collections|n.d.}}

The painting was bought from the Earl of Macclesfield's widow in 1766 by [[Sir Rowland Winn, 5th Baronet]],{{sfn|National Trust Collections|n.d.}} and was hung on the walls of [[Nostell Priory]], near [[Wakefield]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]] for over two centuries by the [[Winn Baronets]] and then their relatives the [[Baron St Oswald|Barons St Oswald]]. Nostell Priory was acquired by the National Trust in 1953, but the former owners retained most of the contents. When the 6th [[Baron St Oswald]] announced his wish to sell the painting in 2002, it was bought by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], with the whole cost of nearly £300,000 funded with a grant from the [[Art Fund]].{{sfn|National Trust Collections|n.d.}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2002}}

